text:
‚Äã¬†@OrthodoxEthos¬†Let me clarify; Christ gives authority directly to all the apostles, but He does not give it in an undifferentiated or flat way.  Peter obviously allowed other offices to exist apart from his distinct role.  Scripture shows a clear distinction between shared apostolic authority and a unique Petrine role. Peter receives the keys of the kingdom personally (Matt 16:19), his name is changed by Christ in a covenantal act, and he is charged alone to shepherd the entire flock (John 21:15‚Äì17). The later extension of binding and loosing to the other apostles does not nullify Peter‚Äôs singular commission; it presupposes it. Authority in Scripture is often shared without being equal in jurisdiction, just as all bishops share the episcopate without eliminating primacy among them. The fact that Peter does not ‚Äúgive‚Äù authority to the others is irrelevant, since Catholic theology does not claim Peter originates authority, only that Christ establishes an office in Peter that endures through succession.

Appeals to the Nicene-Constantinopolitan Creed and the council of 879 do not undermine this. The theological content of the filioque existed in the West centuries before its liturgical insertion, and Rome never denied the Creed‚Äôs faith. The dispute was primarily disciplinary and linguistic, not a sudden doctrinal rupture in which Rome ‚Äúleft the Church.‚Äù The claim that 879 constitutes an ecumenical council binding on Rome is itself contested and depends on a selective use of reception that Orthodoxy does not apply consistently elsewhere. Likewise, portraying Pope Sergius IV in 1009 as the decisive break is historically inaccurate; the filioque was already established in Western usage, and communion between East and West continued in various forms long afterward. The schism was gradual, not the result of a single papal act.

Finally, the argument that ‚ÄúEastern Orthodoxy‚Äù and ‚ÄúRoman Catholicism‚Äù did not yet exist cuts against the Orthodox position, not the Catholic one. If those later categories did not yet exist, then what must be explained is why Rome was uniquely appealed to, corrected other churches, confirmed councils, and exercised authority beyond its local boundaries throughout the first millennium. Honor alone does not account for this pattern. What developed over time was not Roman primacy, which is already visible early on, but Eastern resistance to its implications.
